I kind of understand the frustration over the over the coverage quality. SpaceX has definitely set a very high bar to match.

That being said, I think we need to take a step back and recognize the incredible amount time and resources that all the people at Boeing and NASA have dedicated to helping us advance towards becoming an interstellar civilization. It’s one of the most difficult and important undertakings I think mankind will ever do, and there will undoubtedly be speed bumps along the way. It’s too big a challenge for one company or even one country to accomplish on its own, and it makes me so hopeful for the future.

snippet.textDisplay: We have a private company like SpaceX launching state of the art technology that is fully automated and lands itself, and they broadcast that in 1080p, with cameras everywhere, you don't miss a second of the action. Meanwhile here you have a company that can't even match Airbus in plane technology and the only 21st century aircraft they developed has just killed over 300 people, using 60's technology to launch a fairly conventional spacecraft and land it old-school, and they can't even show us because apparently they couldn't figure out cameras and bandwidth yet. And to do so they require 100 times more money. Are we supposed to be impressed?

snippet.textDisplay: IMHO Boeing ultimately failed to accomplish what Soyuz has been doing for decades, Period! Missing the ISS link up was a bust that should be taken into account when assessing the next contract. Has Boeing begun it's own final descent as a leader in space technology? It must be noted that the Soyuz program had it's significant failures that resulted in cosmonaut deaths. Obviously the evolution to private industry is lacking in the nationwide interest in the 60s and 70s due to the broad technological advances in media choices.
